Details
1. Export syntax forms
- Named export declaration: after 'export' you may use var/let/const/function/class declarations, or an export list referencing previously-declared names.
- Default export: exactly one allowed per module; default can be any expression; function/class default exports may be anonymous and are treated as declarations (hoisted behavior for function declarations applies).

2. Live binding semantics and temporal behavior
- Exports create live bindings: importers see updated values when exported bindings are mutated by the exporting module after evaluation.
- Export declarations themselves are not subject to TDZ for the export statement; you may export a name before its declaration appears in the file because export is a declaration only.

3. Re-export and aggregation semantics
- export from "module" relays named exports from the target without creating local bindings in the current module.
- export * from "mod" re-exports all named exports but not the default; use export { default } from "mod" to re-export default.
- Duplicate star re-exports that produce identical exported names cause the name to be omitted and importing that name directly will throw a SyntaxError in the importing module.

4. Parsing and validity constraints
- Exports are only allowed in module context (not in scripts). Use <script type="module"> or an ES module loader.
- export cannot appear inside block scopes (e.g., inside functions) — top-level only, with specific exceptions for 'export' referencing names declared elsewhere.
- Cannot use more than one default export; exported names must be unique within module export list.

5. Implementation guidance and verification
- When implementing a module bundler or linter, ensure export declarations are discovered at parse-time to build the module namespace map and to support live-binding semantics.
- For re-exports, map the exported name to the target module's exported name and update resolution for specifier resolution rules.

Supplementary details
- Use cases: barrel files that aggregate many submodules use export from "x" to reduce boilerplate. When building barrels, be explicit about default re-exports using export { default as name } from "module".
- Server/loader constraints: relative import specifiers must include file extension when running in browsers and in Node ESM for relative/absolute specifiers.

Reference details (exact patterns and effects)
- Exact syntax tokens recognized: export, default, *, as, from, {, } and variant declarations for let/const/var/function/class.
- Error cases: Duplicate export names -> SyntaxError; multiple default exports -> SyntaxError.
- Module evaluation order: export declarations are recorded during module instantiation; binding values are resolved during module evaluation; imports receive live views of exported bindings.

